04308nam a22005895i 9780774853835DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748538357 a10.59962/97807748538352doi  a(DE-B1597)662007  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKKT1805.D78 2006eb 7aLAW0380302bisacsh04a346.41 aDrummond, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMapping Marriage Law in Spanish Gitano Communities /cSusan Drummond. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Le Guide du Routard -- tState: Intersections in Spanish Family Law -- tCulture: Wanderings and Dwellings -- tMarriage: Hidden and Enacted lus Commune -- tConclusion: Voyage through a Strange City -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tLaw and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aComparative law and legal anthropology have traditionally restricted themselves to their own fields of inquiry. Mapping Marriage Law in Spanish Gitano Communities turns this tendency on its head and investigates what happens when the voices of each discipline are invited to speak to each other. Susan Drummond forges this hybrid form of comparative work through small- and large-scale studies of Gitano marriage law as it emerges in a Western European state, in a modern urban centre, and in particular communities and families. Drummond's mapping of Gitano marriage law is grounded in ethnographic fieldwork in Andalucia. The study draws initially from the tradition of comparative law to focus on the emergence of Spanish state family law in a predominantly national and international context. Drummond then adopts the role of legal anthropologist to examine a particular legal culture that exists within, and also beyond, the Spanish state: that of the Gitanos and the transnational Roma. Ultimately, she brings the international, national, and cultural dimensions of law into play with one another and contemplates how all of these influences bear on the spirit of Andalusian Gitano marriage law. The result is an ethos of marriage law in a thoroughly mixed legal jurisdiction. Mapping Marriage Law in Spanish Gitano Communities will appeal to scholars and students in comparative law and legal anthropology, as well as readers interested in Roma studies in general, and the Gitanos in particular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDomestic relationszSpain. 0aLaw and anthropology. 0aLaw, Romani. 0aMarriage lawzSpain. 0aRomaniesxLegal status, laws, etc.zSpain. 7aLAW / Family Law / Marriage.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485383540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774853835423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774853835/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles